athetic. The boy forgot to bring in his homework. He gave his teacher a sob story and told her that his dog ate it.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>655. sore loser &ndash; person who gets angry when he loses. That little girl is a sore loser. She cries every time she doesn&rsquo;t win a game.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>656. sort of &ndash; almost, not quite, similar to. I&rsquo;m not sure what color this shirt is. It is sort of blue and sort of green.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>657. sourpuss &ndash; a disagreeable person who seldom smiles. My teacher is always in a bad mood. He is such a sourpuss.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>658. spic and span &ndash; very clean, very neat. Now that we have cleaned our house, it looks spic and span.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>659. spill the beans &ndash; tell a secret, inform. She found out a secret and told all of her friends. She spilled the beans.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>660. spine chilling &ndash; terrifying, thrilling. I don&rsquo;t think that young children should see this movie. It is spine chilling.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>661. spitting image &ndash; exact resemblance. The boy is the spitting image of his father. They look like twins.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>662. split hairs &ndash; make trivial, unnecessary distinctions. The lawyers were splitting hairs over the wording in the contract.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>663. split up &ndash; separate. Although they have been married for over 25 years, the couple decided to split up because they could no longer get along.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>664. splurge &ndash; spend a lot of money for something. When it came to buying a new car, they splurged and bought one that was luxurious.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>665. spoiled &ndash; getting and expecting everything one wants. Their children are so spoiled. They have every toy that you can imagine and don&rsquo;t seem to be appreciative.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>666. sport &ndash; a person generous with money. He took me out to dinner and paid for everything. He was very sporty with his money.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>667. spring &ndash; pay. Because he just won some money in a contest, he sprang for dinner.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>668. spruce up &ndash; clean, redecorate. We wanted to make our home look good for the holiday party. We spent days sprucing it up.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>669. square one &ndash; in the beginning. Now that the computer had lost all the information in the report, we will have to begin at square one.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>670. squeal- inform. Even though he was involved in the bank robbery, he squealed on his partner so that he wouldn&rsquo;t have to go to jail.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>671. stab someone in the back &ndash; betray someone. We were always so friendly in the office. I cannot believe that he stabbed me in the back and tried to have me fired.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>672. stand &ndash; tolerate, like. The president would not stand for corruption in his administration.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>673. stand on one&rsquo;s own two feet &ndash; be independent. Once he graduated from college, he was able to get a job and an apartment and he was able to stand on his own two feet.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>674. stand someone up &ndash; fail to keep an appointment or date. They decided to meet at 6:00. She waited for him for an hour and then realized that he stood her up.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>675. stand up to someone &ndash; be brave, courageously confront someone. Even though the bully was twice his size, the boy wasn&rsquo;t afraid and was able to stand up to him.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>676. start the ball rolling &ndash; take the 