eryone took a beating in the stock market.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>697. take a crack at &ndash; try, attempt. Even though you tried to fix the toy and couldn&rsquo;t, let me take a crack at it.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>698. take advantage of &ndash; treat unfairly for your own gain, make good use of time or conditions. Because I had a few days off of work, I took advantage of all the time I had a read a few books.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>699. take after &ndash; resemble or act like a parent or relative. I see that he takes after his dad in his ability to play basketball.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>700. take it &ndash; endure trouble, criticism, abuse, pressure. Everyone in school told her how ugly and stupid she was. She was unable to take it and eventually changed schools.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>');");
E_D("replace into `cn_ecms_news_data_1` values('40','20','','1','0','0','0','','','','<p>&nbsp;701. take on &ndash; begin to handle, commit oneself to, accept. He took on a great challenge when he became the CEO of a bankrupt company.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>702. take one&rsquo;s hat off to someone &ndash; admire, respect, praise. I am very impressed that you actually had your book published. I take my hat off to you!&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>703. take over &ndash; take control, command. When the pilot became ill, the co-pilot had to take over the controls of the aircraft.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>704. take someone for a ride &ndash; cheat, swindle. When my car broke down for the third time, I realized that the car salesman really took me for a ride.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>705. take someone to the cleaners &ndash; win all of someone&rsquo;s money, cheat someone. He invested money in a business deal that went bad. They took him to the cleaners.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>706. take something lying down &ndash; suffer without having a fight. Someone said the he stole money from the company. He&rsquo;s not going to take that lying down.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>707. take something to heart &ndash; consider seriously. His parents spoke to him about improving his grades. I hope he took it to heart.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>708. take a bull by the horns &ndash; take strong action. He needs more money, so he is going to take the bull by the horns and ask for a raise.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>709. take the Fifth &ndash; refuse to testify against oneself, as guaranteed by the Fifth Amendment to the Constitution. He asked the fat girl how much she weighed. She was embarrassed and took the Fifth.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>710. take the plunge &ndash; do something decisive. I realized I gained a lot of weight, so I finally took the plunge and decided to seriously go on a diet.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>711. take the words out of someone&rsquo;s mouth &ndash; say something someone else was going to say. I was just going to say that he was a liar. You took the words right out of my mouth.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>712. take up &ndash; begin an activity or hobby. She plans to take up golf next summer.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>713. take with a grain of salt &ndash; listen with skepticism. He told me that he got all A&rsquo;s in college. I don&rsquo;t believe him. You should take it with a grain of salt.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>714. talk through one&rsquo;s hat &ndash; make exaggerated or inaccurate statements. She&rsquo;s always talking about how much she is investing in the stock market, but I think she is talking through her hat.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>715. talk turkey &ndash; discuss seriously, in a business-like manner. If you are really serious about buying my car, let&rsquo;s talk turkey.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>716. tearjerker &ndash; story that makes you cry. The movie we saw last night was a real tearjerker.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>717. tell someone off &ndash; speak to angrily. Whenever she becomes too arrogant, it is time to tell her off.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>718. think up &ndash; invent, create. The theme for this year&rsquo;s party will not work. We need to think up a new idea.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>719. third degree, the &ndash; prolonged questioning. When I returned home from my date, my roommate wanted to know everything that had happened and gave me the third degree.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>720. through the grapevine &ndash; via gossip from other people. I heard through the grapevine that you are pregnant. Is that true?&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>721. through the mill &ndash; experienced in difficulties of life. She&rsquo;s had a difficult life. She&rsquo;s been put through the mill.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>722. throw cold water on &ndash; discourage. I really don&rsquo;t want to throw cold water on your business proposal, but I really don&rsquo;t think that it is a good idea.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>723. throw in the towel &ndash; surrender, give up. When he realized that there was no way he was going to finish the race, he finally threw in the towel.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>724. throw one&rsquo;s weight around &ndash; use one&rsquo;s influence in a showy manner. Because she was the boss&rsquo;s daughter, she liked throwing her weight around the office and tell everyone what to do.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>725. throw the book at &ndash; punish severely for breaking rules or the law. They have a lot of evidence against that criminal. They are going to throw the book at him at the trial.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>726. tickled pink &ndash; very happy. I wasn&rsquo;t feeling well and wanted to go home. I was tickled pink that the party had finally ended.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>727. tide someone over &ndash; help someone through a shortage. Can you please loan me \$10 and tide me over until I get paid next week?&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>728. tie the knot &ndash; get married. She will tie the knot this spring.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>729. tied down &ndash; restricted by family or job responsibilities. When you have children, pets and a mortgage, you feel tied down.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>730. tight squeeze &ndash; difficult situation financially. I don&rsquo;t have the money for that now. I am in a tight squeeze.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>731. tighten one&rsquo;s belt &ndash; economize, spend and use less. Since he has taken a cut in his salary, the family has needed to tighten their belt.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>732. tightwad &ndash; person who is cheap and stingy. Whenever we go to a restaurant, he always tries to leave without contributing any money toward the bill. He is such a tightwad.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>733. tip someone off &ndash; warn, inform. The burglars were arrested because the police were tipped off.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>734. to a T &ndash; perfectly, exactly. Although you have only been to my house once, you described it to a T!&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>735. to boot &ndash; in addition, also. She is trying to lose weight. So I was surprised that after dinner, she ordered cake and ice cream to boot.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>736. to the hilt &ndash; completely, to the limit. He&rsquo;s borrowed a lot of money against his house. He is mortgaged to the hilt!&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>737. tooth and nail &ndash; as hard as possible, fiercely. Although they were going to take that an account away from me, I fought tooth and nail to keep it.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>738. top-notch &ndash; excellent, the best. He never loses a court case. He is a top-notch attorney.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>739. topsy-turvy &ndash; upside down, in disarray. When you move from one apartment to another, everything is topsy-turvy.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>740. total &ndash; completely ruin. After the accident, my car was totaled and was unable to be fixed.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>741. touch and go &ndash; very dangerous or uncertain. She was sent to the hospital in very poor health. The doctors said that it was touch and go.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>742. tough break &ndash; unlucky event, misfortune. Breaking his leg in the middle of football season was a tough break for John.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>743. tourist trap &ndash; any place that is overpriced and attracts tourists. I hate going to that resort in the summer. They charge hundreds of dollars a night for a tiny room. I think it&rsquo;s a tourist trap.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>744. track down &ndash; search for. The balances in both accounts are not matching. We need to track down the problem.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>745. treat &ndash; pay for someone else. He really helped me complete my project, so I treated him to lunch.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>746. try something out &ndash; test. The store told me that we can try the mattress out for 30 days to see if we like it.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>747. turn one off &ndash; disgust, bore, repel. When he started saying bad things about my sister, it really turned me off.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>748. turn out &ndash; result, end. Although the movie was boring at first, it turned out to be wonderful.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>749. turn over a new leaf &ndash; change one&rsquo;s conduct for the better. My little boy has recently started lying to his mother. After I spoke with him, he told me that he is turning over a new leaf and won&rsquo;t do it anymore.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>750. turn someone down &ndash; reject. Although the job interview went very well, he was turned down for the job.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>751. turn someone&rsquo;s stomach &ndash; get someone sick and upset. It really turns my stomach when little children treat their elders poorly.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>752. turn the tables &ndash; reverse the situation. We lost the game last night, but tonight, we&rsquo;ll turn the tables.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>753. turn to &ndash; go to for help. He was such a good friend. I always knew that I could turn to him if I needed some money.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>754. turn up &ndash; appear. Those keys have been lost for a month. I am hoping that they turn up soon.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>755. twiddle one&rsquo;s thumbs &ndash; not busy, not working. Our department has gotten slow this season. All we are doing is twiddling our thumbs.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>756. twist someone around one&rsquo;s finger &ndash; influence someone easily. He will do whatever she wants. It&rsquo;s amazing how she has him twisted around her little finger.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>757. two-faced &ndash; disloyal, untrustworthy. She&rsquo;ll tell you that you have a beautiful dress, but when you leave, she&rsquo;ll say that you are fat and how awful it looked on you. She is two-faced.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>758. under the table &ndash; illegal money transaction, such as paying a bribe. She was paid under the table and continued to collect her unemployment checks illegally.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>759. under the weather &ndash; not feeling well. I started sneezing this morning and have had a bad headache. I am beginning to feel under the weather.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>760. up one&rsquo;s alley &ndash; something one enjoys, special interest. I&rsquo;m going to the art museum on Sunday. I know you love to paint, so this is right up your alley.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>761. up the river &ndash; in jail. The judge found him guilty and he was sent up the river for 5 years.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>762. up to here with &ndash; disgusted with another&rsquo;s continual behavior. My phone bills are always so high. I am just up to here with them.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>763. up to one&rsquo;s ears &ndash; deeply immersed in. I have a lot of folders sitting on my desk. I am up to my ears in paperwork.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>764. up to par (neg.)&ndash; meeting normal standards. I have a headache and don&rsquo;t feel up to par.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>765. up to someone &ndash; someone&rsquo;s choice. Because it is her birthday, it is up to her what kind of birthday cake to buy.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>766. upset the applecart &ndash; ruin or spoil a plan or idea. Our plans are perfect. Don&rsquo;t discuss them with anyone. We don&rsquo;t want to upset the applecart.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>767. use one&rsquo;s noodle (head) &ndash; think. He wasn&rsquo;t using his noodle when he offered to stay and clean up the mess.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>768. walk all over someone &ndash; take advantage of someone. He loves her so much and she walks all over him.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>769. wash one&rsquo;s hands of &ndash; refuse responsibility for, abandon. If he lies or hurts you, you should wash your hands of him.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>770. washed up &ndash; no longer successful or needed, failed. Since he was arrested, his movie career is all washed up.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>771. waste one&rsquo;s breath &ndash; speak or argue with no result. I have told her that she should stop smoking a thousand times. Don&rsquo;t even mention it to her, you&rsquo;ll be wasting your breath.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>772. watch (or mind) one&rsquo;s P&rsquo;s and Q&rsquo;s &ndash; act very carefully, pay attention to detail. If you are having dinner with your boss, you have to watch your P&rsquo;s and Q&rsquo;s.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>773. water down &ndash; dilute. The coffee is too strong. I think you need to water it down.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>774. wear the pants &ndash; be the boss of the family. She makes all the big decisions when it comes to finances. We all know who wears the pants in that family.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>775. weigh one&rsquo;s words &ndash; be careful of what one says. The boss is going to interview me today. I don&rsquo;t want to talk too much. I should weigh my words.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>776. well-off &ndash; rich, wealthy. She has traveled extensively throughout the world. I believe she&rsquo;s very well-off.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>777. wet behind the ears &ndash; inexperienced. He can&rsquo;t manage the office. He is still wet behind the ears.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>778. wet blanket &ndash; person who discourages others from having fun. She was no fun at the party. She is a wet blanket.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>779. wet one&rsquo;s whistle &ndash; have a drink, especially alcohol. I am so thirsty. I would like to wet my whistle.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>780. what it takes &ndash; any ability for a job, courage. She is smart and ambitious. She certainly has what it takes to be a doctor.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>781. when the chips are down &ndash; at the worst time, when one faces the biggest obstacles. A true friend is someone who is always there when the chips are down.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>782. whistle a different tune &ndash; change one&rsquo;s attitude, contradict previous ideas. The boss&rsquo;s son doesn&rsquo;t believe his father should pay anyone overtime, but when he can work extra hours, he whistles a different tune.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>783. white as a ghost - very pale because of fear, shock, illness. My sister became as white as a ghost when she saw the man at the window.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>784. white lie - a harmless lie (told to be polite or to do something not seriously wrong). I told my boss a white lie and said that I was sick yesterday when I actually wasn&rsquo;t.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>785. wild goose chase &ndash; absurd or hopeless search. She did not want the police to find her boyfriend so she gave them false information and sent them on a wild goose chase.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>786. will power &ndash; strength of mind. Some people say you need a lot of will power to quit smoking.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>787. wimp &ndash; spineless, non-assertive person. He never speaks up for himself. He is such a wimp.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>788. wind up &ndash; end, finish. It&rsquo;s getting late and I want to finish this project and go home. Let&rsquo;s wind things up.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>789. wing it &ndash; rely only on one&rsquo;s knowledge, act without preparation. They asked me to make a speech, but I did not prepare anything so I just winged it.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>790. wisecrack &ndash; sarcastic or nasty remark. He is not very nice, so don&rsquo;t be surprised if he makes a wisecrack about your clothes.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>791. wishy-washy &ndash; having no definite opinion, unable to decide. He never has his own opinion. He is very wishy-washy.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>792. with a fine toothed comb &ndash; very carefully. She lost her earring somewhere in our house. We searched for it with a fine-toothed comb.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>793. with flying colors - with great or total success. She passed her course with flying colors and now wants to go out and celebrate.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>794. within reason &ndash; sensible, reasonable, reasonably. I know you want to buy my car. If your offer is within reason, then it&rsquo;s a deal.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>795. word of mouth &ndash; recommendation from other people. His business does not advertise. He became successful all by word of mouth.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>796. work one&rsquo;s fingers to the bone &ndash; work very hard. I had to type many pages to put this book together. I have worked my fingers to the bone.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>797. work out &ndash; find an answer, solve. I have added these numbers three times and still get different answers. This problem can&rsquo;t seem to be worked out.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>798. wrong side of the tracks, the &ndash; the poor section of town, implying social inferiority. She comes from a wealthy family. Her parents did not want her to marry anyone from the wrong side of the tracks.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>799. yell bloody murder &ndash; express loud, emotional anger. Some babies yell bloody murder if their mothers leave them with babysitters.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>800. You&rsquo;re kidding &ndash; Really? Is it true? You&rsquo;ve read every single entry in this book? You&rsquo;re kidding!</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>');");
E_D("replace into `cn_ecms_news_data_1` values('34','20','','1','0','0','0','','','','<p>101. cinch &ndash; easy. Adding and subtracting was always a cinch.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>102. clamp down &ndash; become stricter. Because he came home from the party so late, his father said he will start to clamp down on his curfew.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>103. clean up &ndash; make a big profit. Since he started his new business, he&rsquo;s really cleaning up.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>104. clear &ndash; go through. When will this check clear my bank?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>105. clear the air &ndash; calm anger and remove misunderstanding. We were tired of fighting, so we decided to start talking and clear the air.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>106. close shave &ndash; narrow escape. It was a close shave getting out of the burning building.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>107. coast is clear &ndash; no enemy is in sight. Take the present out of the closet when the coast is clear.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>108. come a long way &ndash; make great progress. He came a long way in his recovery from surgery.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>109. come across &ndash; find or meet by chance. If you come across any pictures of my friends from high school, let me know.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>110. come apart at the seams &ndash; be upset and lose control. I almost came apart at the seams when I saw the taxicab hit my car.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>111. come clean &ndash; tell the truth. I came clean when I knew I was caught in a lie.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>112. come hell or high water &ndash; no matter what happens. Come hell or high water, I&rsquo;ll for sure be at that meeting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>113. come off it &ndash; stop kidding, boasting or making believe. Herbert said he was the only one who could do the job. I told him to come off it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>114. come on strong - overwhelm with excessively strong language or personality. The car salesman came on too strong and angered my wife.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>115. come through with flying colors &ndash; succeed, win, exceed. When he graduated with honors, it was evident that he came through with flying color.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>116. comeback &ndash; to be successful again. The actress made an outstanding comeback on the stage, after her bout with pneumonia.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>117. con &ndash; lie, swindle, trick. His boss conned him into working on the weekend for no pay.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>118. cook someone&rsquo;s goose &ndash; create big problems for someone. He knew that when he was caught in a lie his goose was cooked.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>119. cough up &ndash; give money unwillingly, give up a secret. You said that you would help pay for their wedding. Well, it&rsquo;s been three months &ndash; cough it up.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>120. count on &ndash; rely on, trust. I could always count on my best friend.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>121. cover for someone &ndash; protect someone. Please cover me, if I end up not knowing what to say at the meeting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>122. crack down &ndash; The police are beginning to crack down on teenagers who are out too late at night.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>123. cream of the crop &ndash; the best of a group, top-choice. This university only accepts the cream of the crop.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>124. creeps, the &ndash; fear, uneasiness. It gives me the creeps every time I pass the strange looking house.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>125. crocodile tears - show of sorrow that is not really felt. He cried crocodile tears when he discovered that he couldn&rsquo;t go to the meeting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>126. crop up &ndash; happen quickly without warning. I had to stay at work late yesterday. Some new work cropped up.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>127. cross one&rsquo;s mind &ndash; think of, occur quickly to someone. It did not cross my mind to thank her for my birthday card.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>128. cut corners &ndash; limit one&rsquo;s buying. She was way over budget for the wedding, so she needed to cut corners.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>129. cut down on &ndash; use less, reduce. My doctor wants me to cut down on sugar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>130. cut the mustard - succeed, do well enough what needs to be done. He wasn&rsquo;t able to cut the mustard so he had to leave the army after only one year.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>131. cut out &ndash; have talent for, be suited for. She is not cut out for the swim team. She&rsquo;s too slow.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>132. cut someone down to size &ndash; prove someone is not as good as he or she thinks. John thought he was the smartest student in the class. We needed to cut him down to size.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>133. dawn on &ndash; become clear, begin to understand. It finally dawned on me that I missed our anniversary.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>134. dead-end job &ndash; position with no future. He decided to go back to college because he realized he had a dead- end job.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>135. dig up &ndash; find, recall, discover. Have you dug up any information on the new employee?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>136. dime a dozen &ndash; common, easily obtained. Those shiny stones are not worth anything. They are a dime a dozen.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>137. dish out &ndash; criticize, abuse, scold - Sometimes he&rsquo;s nasty and insulting. He can really dish out.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>138. dive &ndash; disreputable, low class bar or nightclub. I did not like where he brought me last night. It was a real dive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>139. do the trick &ndash; be successful, achieve a good result. The recipe needs a little help. I think salt may do the trick.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>140. do without &ndash; live without something. When the television broke, I knew that I could do without it for a week or two.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>141. doctor it up &ndash; fix temporarily. The hem on the dress ripped. I doctored it up with some tape.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>142. double check &ndash; reinvestigate thoroughly, look again for errors. This column does not add up. I will double check it for a mistake.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>143. double-cross &ndash; betray. I cannot double-cross my best friend.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>144. dough &ndash; money. He makes a lot of dough.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>145. down and out &ndash; having no money, no success. Although he was successful a few years ago, today I hear he&rsquo;s down and out.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>146. down in the dumps &ndash; unhappy. She&rsquo;s been down in the dumps ever since she lost her job.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>147. down the drain &ndash; wasted, lost. I don&rsquo;t like to throw my money down the drain.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>148. down to earth &ndash; having good sense, practical. My fianc&eacute;e is friendly and sensible. She&rsquo;s very down to earth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>149. draw the line &ndash; set the limit. He sets an early curfew for his children. He draws the line at 10:00 PM.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>150. dress up &ndash; wear one&rsquo;s best clothing. We need to dress up for this wedding.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>151. dressed to kill - wear one&rsquo;s finest clothing. She was dressed to kill when I saw her at the convention last year.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>152. dribs and drabs &ndash; little by little, small quantities. She told us the story in dribs and drabs.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>153. drive at &ndash; try to say, insinuate. What were you driving at when you said that insulting comment?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>154. drive someone up a wall &ndash; make someone crazy. My son is driving me up a wall!&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>155. drop in the bucket &ndash; a small amount. The cost of fixing the sink is a drop in the bucket compared to replacing the whole sink.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>156. drop out &ndash; one who doesn&rsquo;t complete a study course. My cousin dropped out of college.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>157. drown one&rsquo;s sorrows &ndash; drink liquor to forget one&rsquo;s problems. I was so upset last night, that I drowned my sorrows at the bar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>158. dump &ndash; get rid of, reject &ndash; I can&rsquo;t believe you dumped your girlfriend.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>159. dwell on &ndash; talk and think about something all the time. I know it is a big decision, but you shouldn&rsquo;t dwell on it all day.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>160. eager beaver &ndash; ambitious, hard working. Charlie gets to work at 7:00 am everyday. He is an eager beaver.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>161. earful &ndash; interesting gossip, information. My friend found out about the local politician. I got an earful.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>162. egg someone on &ndash; push, urge. My wife didn&rsquo;t want to take the job, but I egged her on.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>163. elbow grease &ndash; strength for cleaning. I needed to use a lot of elbow grease to get the dirt off the floor.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>164. elbow room &ndash; enough space to be comfortable. It was so tight in that restaurant. There wasn&rsquo;t any elbow room.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>165. end up &ndash; finish. I heard that you got lost on your way home last night. Where did you end up?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>166. every Tom, Dick and Harry &ndash; the average person, nobody special. It seemed like every Tom, Dick and Harry came out to purchase tickets for the movie.&nbsp;</p